[normal]Since 1973, Campaign for Better Transport has been helping to create transport policies and programmes that give people better lives and support the environment. Our 
[normal]vision is a country where communities have affordable transport that improves quality of l
[normal]ife and protects the environment. Achieving our vision requires substantial changes to UK transport policy
[normal] which w
[normal]e aim to achieve 
[normal]by 
[normal]providing well-researched, practical solutions that gain support from 
[normal]both 
[normal]decision-makers and the public.
[normal]The Government published 
[normal]Action for Roads
[normal] in July 2013, following up the spending plans ini
[normal]tially announced in the Spending Round in June and outlined in 
[normal]Investing in Britain's Future
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A) Policies we welcome[bold]These include a renewed emphasis on maintenance, the ability 
[normal]of
[normal] the Highways Agency to fund projects outside the strategic road network, specific policies on cycling and walking, and a range of initiatives to reduce the environmental and landscape impact of new and existing roads. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]B) An unwelcome[bold] (and irrational) [bold]re[bold]turn to 'predict and provide'[bold]We are very concerned with several of the assumptions 
[normal]behind the policies in
[normal] 
[normal]Action for Roads
[normal]:
[normal]1. The UK's strategic road network
[normal] (SRN)
[normal] is inadequate
[normal]2. Traffic growth and new roads to accommodate it are essential for economic
[normal] growth
[normal]3. Forecasts predict traffic will grow rapidly
[normal]4. A large road-building programme will reduce congestion in the long term
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We will tackle the third assumption in answer to the 
[normal]C
[normal]ommittee's third question, below.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The first assumption 
[normal]has been
[normal] stated
[normal] repeatedly in recent documents and speeches: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However
[normal], this statistic 
[normal]turns out to be
[normal] based on the replie
[normal]s
[normal] of 
[normal]a sample of 
[normal]company executives
[normal] 
[normal]to a single survey question
[normal] in the World Economic Forum’s
[normal] 
[normal]annual Executive Opinion Survey
[normal].
[normal] In 2012, the sample size for thi
[normal]s survey from the UK was just 93.
[normal]  
[normal]In contrast, t
[normal]he
[normal] much more rigorous and extensive
[normal] Eddington 
[normal]Transport Study of
[normal] 2006 found that the UK was very well connected in transport terms, with good 
[normal]networks linking
[normal] major towns and cities and many alternative rou
[normal]tes provi
[normal]ding a high level of resilience.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Action for Roads
[normal] provide
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]no
