[normal]The whole of Section 1 on 'Roads and the economy' only includes two references to external analyses (the other references are to basic 
[normal]statistics for chart data) and these are both relatively limited surveys of businesses (the WEF and an EEF document based on a survey of manufacturing companies
[normal]). The Government should be challenged on the why it has used such small and narrow range of so
[normal]urces as a key supporting plank for a major new policy and spending programme.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In terms of policies to support economic growth, the Eddington Study also contradicts the assertion that large new road infrastructure will deliver growth
[normal], saying: "Today, in m
[normal]ature economies like the UK, with well-established networks and where connectivity between economic centres is already in place, the evidence suggests that there is considerably less scope for transport improvements to deliver the periods of rapid growth s
[normal]een historically." 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Eddington 
[normal]also 
[normal]recognis
[normal]ed that congestion is primarily an urban problem and championed smaller, low-cost interventions based on evidence of the benefits of "smarter choices" programmes and the cycling demonstration towns. Since then, 
[normal]the 
[normal]evidence
[normal] base
[normal] 
[normal]for this approach 
[normal]has grown
[normal] rapidly
[normal], with the Local Sustainable Transport Fund supporting nearly 100 packages of projects and initial (as yet unpublished) assessments showing
[normal] very high benefit-cost ratios.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]M
[normal]any UK cities, such as Notting
[normal]ham, Cambridge and London, have shown that economic and population growth can be achieved without corresponding traffic increases
[normal] and, across
[normal] the country, traffic and economic growth have been decoupling since the 1990s
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Other recent evidence comes from t
[normal]he USA where research into stimulus spending has shown that a 'fix it first' strategy is more effective than 
[normal]big new 
[normal]road-
[normal]building
[normal] projects
[normal] at creating jobs
[normal].
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Even on its own terms, the fourth assumption
