[normal]A) Why traffic forecasts matter[bold]The problem with over-estimating traff
[normal]ic growth lies not only in how forecasts
[normal] are used to support policies of 'predict and provide' (in fact they could equally support
[normal] urgent
[normal] 
[normal]policies of traffic reduction) 
[normal]but also in how they 
[normal]underlie
[normal] economic case
[normal]s for
[normal] schemes and
[normal] 
[normal]lend systematic
[normal] support
[normal] to
[normal] 
[normal]projects
[normal] that add road capacity. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The WebTAG method of 
[normal]assessment
[normal] – in particular the 
[normal]way 
[normal]cost-benefit ratio
[normal]s are calculated
[normal] – rel
[normal]ies 
[normal]he
[normal]avily 
[normal]on 
[normal]forecasts of
[normal] traffic
[normal] growth
[normal]. Time savings 
[normal]often
[normal] 
[normal]constitute
[normal] 
[normal]eighty to ninety per cent
[normal] of the calculated benefits of a scheme (the controversial Bexhill-Hastings Link Road is a typical example at 
[normal]84
[normal]%
[normal]) 
[normal]and 
[normal]the
[normal]se
[normal] time 'savings' are 
[normal]calculated against
[normal] 
[normal]what is predicted to be the case with no 
[normal]scheme in place.
[normal] It is 
[normal]mainly 
[normal]because
[normal] strong long-term traffic growth 
[normal]is
[normal] predicted that 
[normal]time savings
[normal] 
[normal]tend to dominate BCRs
[normal].
