[normal]D[bold])[bold] Problems[bold] with the underlying National Transport Model[bold] (NTM)[bold]The main problems with the methodology behind forecasts and the underlying NTM are the limited number of 'key drivers' and a number of out-of-date assumptions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Road Transport Forecasts 2013
[normal] outlines the
[normal]se three key drivers and their assumed effects on traffic
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As the NTM is a closed model, it is not possible to interrogate its detailed workings. However we believe that the National Trip End Model (NTEM) does co
[normal]nsider factors such as population density, new developments and demographics in working out local variations in demand for travel by car, but that ultimately these are 'constrained' or adjusted to fit in with the macro picture determined by these three fac
[normal]tors. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]By using so few factors in estimating macro-level changes in demand, the forecasts ignore
[normal] how open to question future behaviour is and leave aside a range of important nation
[normal]wide changes in 
[normal]technology
[normal], demographics
[normal] and 
[normal]land-use
[normal]. These failings are 
[normal]acknowledged in the chapter 'Uncertainty and modelling' in the forecast documents, but
[normal] they
[normal] are currently not used to alter the model:  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Changes in technology[bold] and connectivity[bold] that affect behaviour[bold] – especially relevant to the steady reduction in trip rat
[normal]es seen since 1997
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Changes in culture[bold] between generations[bold] – younger people are currently assumed as they age to adopt the driving patterns 
[normal]of
[normal] people in today's older age groups. It is much more likely that 
[normal]people
[normal] raised since the 1990s will have different 
[normal]driving habits
[normal] to those growing
[normal] up in the 1970s or 1950s. 
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Changes in town planning[bold] – for example the 'town centre first' planning policies that are attributed to a proportion of the reduction in driving seen in the 'On the Move' report (see next section).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Out of date assumptions[bold]The following assumptions 
[normal]are 
[normal]also 
[normal]out of date. 
[normal]There are plans to update these in the near future, but this is not represented in the 2013 forecasts
[normal] upon which
[normal] the policies in
[normal] 
[normal]Action for Roads 
[normal]re
[normal]ly.
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Trip rates[bold] – the 2013 Road Transport Forecasts document admits that trip rate data
[normal] is based on NTS results from 1988-96 and that they are assumed to be constant over time for each type of person (split according to age, car ownership and employment)
[normal] 
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Population dis[bold]tribution[bold] – the NTEM uses 
[normal]ONS
[normal] population projections from 2010.
[normal] These are in turn based on 
[normal]data
[normal] from the 2001 census. The next set of detailed data on population, 
[normal]from
[normal] the 2011 Census, is likely to show a higher level of overall population growth but a ve
[normal]ry different distribution, focused mainly on larger cities that have lower cultural and practical levels of car use and be
[normal]tter public transport
[normal].
