[normal], 
[normal]but
[normal] all the models described above have also proved very unpopular
[normal] with the public
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Our response to 
[normal]Alan 
[normal]Cook
[normal]'s
[normal] review of the Highways Agency, 
[normal]A fresh start for the strategic road network
[normal],
[normal] welcomed its emphasis on better managing the network rather than major expansion. 
[normal]Howe
[normal]ver, we had serious doubts about taking primary responsibility for the SRN away from the Secretary of State for Transport. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Another concern was the proposed remit for the DfT as a 'champion of road users'. The response of the
[normal] then
[normal] Secretary of State to th
[normal]is proposal was relatively robust, saying:
[normal]"
[normal]We accept this recommendation though with some qualifications.
[normal] 
[normal]It is clearly important for the Government to represent the interests of road users as, in the absence of a commercial relationship between drivers 
[normal]and the network operator, customers rely on the Government to feed back their concerns and represent their interests. However, in order to reach balanced and well informed decisions, the Government also needs to take full account of all stakeholders in the
[normal] roads, including the wider community that this network serves."
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However,
[normal] it appears
[normal] these qualifications have not emerged intact from the
[normal] processes that led to
[normal] 
[normal]Action for Roads
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Finally, we question whether
[normal] all
[normal] the aims for the 
[normal]new roads strategy given in the Secretary of State's response to Cook are 
[normal]in fact
[normal] being delivered.
[normal] 
[normal]These
[normal] aims
[normal] 
[normal]included demand management, but there is no sign of policies for managing demand in 
[normal]Action for Roads
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]October 2013
[normal]&#xa0;
